'''Chung Yoo-ra''' (born '''Chung Yoo-yeon''', 30 October 1996) is a South Korean [[equestrianism|equestrian]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fei.org/bios/Person/10110814 |title=Yoora Chung |publisher=fei.org |accessdate=7 October 2016}}</ref> She competed in the [[2014 Asian Games]], where her team won a gold medal.<ref>{{cite news |last=Park |first=Sojung |title=S. Korea wins gold in team dressage equestrian at Asiad |url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/topic/2014/09/20/90/1350010000AEN20140920003001315F.html |date=20 September 2014 |newspaper=[[Yonhap]] |access-date=7 October 2016}}</ref>

She is a daughter of [[Chung Yoon-hoi]] and his ex-wife [[Choi Soon-sil]],<ref>{{cite web|author=8:12 AM ET |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2016/10/29/499864915/swirling-scandal-involving-shamanistic-cult-threatens-s-korean-president |title=Swirling Scandal Involving Shamanistic Cult Threatens South Korean President Park Geun-hye : The Two-Way |publisher=NPR |date=2016-10-29 |accessdate=2017-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Kim |first=Oi-hyun |title=Pres. Park's former aide and his wife may be at the center of ongoing scandal |url=http://english.hani.co.kr/arti/english_edition/e_national/667320.html |date=3 December 2014 |newspaper=[[The Hankyoreh]] |access-date=7 October 2016}}</ref> who has been arrested amid the [[2016 South Korean political scandal]] for using her friendship with the president [[Park Geun-hye]] to illegally interfere in the state affairs, and solicit business donations from top South Korean firms, including [[Samsung]], for a non-profit fund she controlled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-37831514 |title=South Korea scandal: President Park's friend Choi detained - BBC News |publisher=Bbc.com |date= |accessdate=2017-03-24}}</ref>

==Legal issues==
During the investigations of the 2016 South Korean political scandal, Chung Yoo-ra's admission to [[Ewha Womans University]] was cancelled due to "preferential treatment in admissions and grading".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2016/11/116_218514.html|title=Chung Yoo-ra's admission to Ewha to be canceled|date=2016-11-18|newspaper=koreatimes|access-date=2016-11-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20161118000615|title=Chung illegally admitted to Ewha University: ministry|last=Herald|first=The Korea|date=2016-11-18|access-date=2016-11-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2016/11/116_218696.html|title=Prosecutors raid university over influence-peddling scandal|date=2016-11-22|newspaper=koreatimes|access-date=2016-11-28}}</ref> Her high school diploma has been cancelled as well due to falsified high school records.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2016/12/116_219515.html|title=Choi Soon-sil's daughter stripped of high school diploma|date=2016-12-05|newspaper=koreatimes|access-date=2016-12-05}}</ref>

In December 2016, South Korea put out an arrest warrant for Chung Yoo-ra for charges including [[obstruction of justice]], after she refused to return from [[Germany]] to attend a parliamentary inquiry into her role in the scandal.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/what-we-know-about-chung-yoo-ra-daughter-of-key-figure-in-south-koreas-corruption|title=What we know about Chung Yoo Ra, daughter of key figure in South Korea's corruption scandal involving President Park|last=|first=|date=23 December 2016|work=|newspaper=[[The Straits Times]]|access-date=2 January 2017|via=}}</ref> The South Korean government announced that it would invalidate her passport and seek her arrest and [[extradition]] from Germany.<ref name=":0" /> The South Korean government also sought the help of [[Interpol]] to track her down.<ref name=":1">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-38487037|title=South Korea scandal: Daughter of Choi Soon-sil arrested|last=|first=|date=2 January 2017|work=|newspaper=[[BBC News]]|language=en-GB|access-date=2 January 2017|via=}}</ref> On January 1, 2017, she was arrested in [[Aalborg]], [[Denmark]] after a tip from South Korean journalists who had tracked her.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.mynewsdesk.com/dk/nordjyllands-politi/pressreleases/south-korean-woman-detained-by-danish-police-1717217|title=South Korean woman detained by Danish police|newspaper=Mynewsdesk|access-date=2017-01-02}}</ref><ref name=":1" />

The German [[Federal Police (Germany)|Federal Police]] are investigating Chung Yoo-ra and her mother for [[money laundering]] involving assets estimated at more than 1 billion US dollars.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://m.sports.khan.co.kr/view.html?artid=201612271514003&code=540201&pt=nv|title=PD Report Tracking down Chung Yoo-Ra Runaway Footsteps in German|newspaper=Sports Kyung Hyang|access-date=2017-01-02}}</ref><ref name=":1" />
<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://imnews.imbc.com/replay/2017/nw1200/article/4196617_21376.html|title=German Police keep investigating Chung Yoo Ra Money Laundering Case in German|newspaper=MBC|access-date=2017-01-04}}</ref><ref name=":1" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/news/2017/02/22/57/0200000000AEN20170222008951315F.html |title=(LEAD) Danish court extends detention of daughter of woman at center of Korean scandal |publisher=English.yonhapnews.co.kr |date= |accessdate=2017-03-24}}</ref>

