'''Ticketbud''' is an [[event management]], ticketing and registration [[SaaS]] platform for event organizers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.crunchbase.com/organization/ticketbud|title=Crunchbase Profile: Ticketbud|publisher=Crunchbase}}</ref> The software allows event organizers to sell tickets to events and also to promote and market their events on [[Facebook]], [[Twitter]], and [[Instagram]]. Founded in 2009 in [[Austin]], [[Texas]], Ticketbud's revenue is derived from a fee placed upon tickets sold through its software at $0.99 + 2% of the ticket's value per ticket. It places no fee upon events which cost nothing to enter, and due to its involvement with non-profits it offers a reduced rate for organizations under [[501(c)(3)]] designation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nonprofitmatrix.com/ticketbud/|title=Non Profit Matrix Profile: Ticketbud|publisher=Non Profit Matrix}}</ref>
== Products and Features== *On Ticketbud, organizers are given a basic event page which can be modified, including features such as donation tickets, "comped" tickets, discount codes, and RSVPs.<ref name=interview>{{cite web|url=http://www.texastechpulse.com/ticketbud_s_plans_to_transform_online_event_ticketing_with_lynn_yeldell/s-0051841.html |title=Ticketbud's Plans to Transform Online Event Ticketing |publisher=Texas Tech Pulse |date= |accessdate=2015-05-12}}</ref> Unlike most of its competitors, however, it does not yet offered reserved seating.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capterra.com/ticketing-software/spotlight/125237/Ticketbud/Ticketbud |title=Capterra Profile: Ticketbud|publisher=Capterra}}</ref> *Ticketbud maintains event ticketing mobile apps for event organizers on both [[Android (operating system)|Android]] and [[iOS]] devices. The app allows organizers to scan tickets, manage their events, and view real-time attendee data. It also offers [[mobile ticketing]] options for ticket purchasers.<ref name="Blinklist">{{cite web|url=http://blinklist.com/reviews/ticketbud|title= Ticketbud Review: Creating Your Own Events to Sell Tickets}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Macmillan|first=Douglas|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/digits/2014/03/13/eventbrite-tops-billion-dollar-valuation-with-new-funding/|title=Eventbrite Tops Billion-Dollar Valuation With New Funding|publisher=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=2015-05-12|date=23 March 2014}}</ref> *The company runs an event planning blog for planners and marketers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.ticketbud.com/|title=Event Planning Blog|publisher=Ticketbud}}</ref>
==Funding== In 2011, Ticketbud received $1.2 million in its Series A round of funding.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://angel.co/ticketbud|title=Angel.co Profile: Ticketbud|publisher=Angel.co}}</ref><ref name=interview />
